## Git Workflow:
You create a new file, then signal Git to track it with `$ git add...`, make a commit with `$ git commit -m "Message"`, and push it to the remote repository with `$ git push`.

### Common Git Commands:
- Initialize a Git repository: `$ git init` (turns the current folder into a Git repository)
- Check Git configuration: `$ git config --list`
- View Git status: `$ git status`
- Add a file to be tracked: `$ git add file-name`
- Add all files: `$ git add .`
- Commit changes with a message: `$ git commit -m "Commit message"`
- Show details of the last commit: `$ git show`
- View commit logs: `$ git log`
- Push changes to a remote repository: `$ git push`
- Pull updates from the remote repository: `$ git pull`
- Add a remote repository: `$ git remote add origin <URL>`

